docs.snippet: The Presidential primaries of past years have produced a mixed bag of results. They have materially helped some candidates, such as Dwight Eisenhower in 1952. They have eliminated others, such as Wendell Willkie in 1944. But in most cases they have...
docs.lead_paragraph: The Presidential primaries of past years have produced a mixed bag of results. They have materially helped some candidates, such as Dwight Eisenhower in 1952. They have eliminated others, such as Wendell Willkie in 1944. But in most cases they have proved to be unreliable political barometers, such as when Estes Kefauver won all but one of the fifteen primaries he entered in 1952 but failed to come within hailing distance of the Democratic nomination.
